Because embeddings are trained using large corpuses of text, they have a tendancy to learn biases that exist in the text. This can be problematic, especially when such systems are deployed on a large scale. For instance, Dr. Latanya Sweeney (a Harvard professor) authored
detailing Google's tendancy to deliver arrest record ads in response to search queries containing names historically more popular among Black Americans.
Removing bias from NLP models can be an extraordinarily difficult challenge. Within this assignment, we will attempt to do so using a method similar to (but greatly simplified from) that outlined in

In particular, our objective is to to remove gendered bias from terms that should not be gendered. Consider the examples below. Notice that the cosine similarity between "woman" and "engineer" is much lower than that between "man" and "engineer". Similarly, the word "nurse" is much more similar to "woman" than to "man".
To address this issue, we must start by identifying the "gender dimension". This will be a direction (a vector) along which gender differences tend to fall.

To identify this vector, we will use pairs of clearly gendered terms such as "man" and "woman", "father" and "mother", etc. We want to find a single direction that can explain the gender difference of words and will then follow this process:

Now that we have a bias vector representing the gendered dimension, we can pass in vectors and remove bias that exists within that dimension.

that, when provided with a bias vector and a second vector, returns a third vector. In technical terms, the third vector should be a projection onto the bias vector's orthogonal complement (the set of all vectors orthogonal to the bias vector). In simpler terms, you should remove the portion of the second vector that runs parallel to the bias vector so that the dot product between the third vector and the bias vector is zero (within computer precision).
